    "To estimate the standard errors, we use the Jackknife Variance Estimation.",
    "The first research question studies the impact of GitHub Copilot on the volume of innovation with the raw count of commits received per quarter as the dependent variable.",
    "Table 3 presents the estimation results by separately analyzing the matched language pairs using three approaches: the classical TWFE DiD (Columns 1 and 4), a balanced panel sample which retains packages that were released before our data collection period, thus controlling for newer packages with potentially higher activity (Columns 2 and 5), and the SDiD estimation using balanced panel (Columns 3 and 6).",
    "For Python versus R (Columns 1-3), GitHub",
    "Copilot increases commits by 6.816 per quarter (column 1), which represents a 37.05% increase relative to the pre-treatment mean of 18.395 commits per quarter."
